# Events Module

**Location**: `Code/PigeonLib/Pigeon/Events/`

---

## Module Purpose and Responsibilities

The Events module defines the **platform-to-engine event pipeline**. It covers two distinct stages:

1. **Platform event objects** (`Event` and its subclasses, in `Pigeon/Events/`) — typed, polymorphic objects that the platform window creates from OS messages (Win32 `WM_*`) and hands to `Application::OnEvent`.
2. **ECS event components** (in `Pigeon/Core/`) — plain structs that carry the same payload into the ECS `World` so that systems can read them during `Update()`. These are the *only* form that systems ever see.

The module's contract: raw OS input arrives as a platform event object; `Application::OnEvent` immediately fans it out both into any direct bookkeeping (resize/close) and into the ECS registry via `World::EmplaceExternalEvent`; all event entities are destroyed at the end of the same `World::Update` call.

> **Design note (from source comment)**: Events are currently **blocking and synchronous** — they are dispatched at the instant the OS delivers them. The comment in `Event.h` acknowledges that a buffered event-bus approach (process events at a defined stage each frame) may be preferable in the future.

